  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transactions or commercial activities. This process makes the money appear to come from a legitimate source.\n\nMoney laundering is a serious criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world. It is often associated with other crimes such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism financing. Governments and international organizations have established stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and individuals or entities found guilty of this crime can face severe penalties, including hefty fines and imprisonment.\n\nFinancial institutions and certain businesses are also required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities to the relevant authorities.",
